import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';

const frontmatter = {
  title: 'Built for Tomorrow',
  description: 'Silica\'s Security Model and Post-Quantum Resilience. Designed with post-quantum-secure cryptography from the ground up.',
  author: 'Silica Network Team',
  date: 'December 4, 2024',
  category: 'Security',
  readingTime: '6 min read'
};
---

<BlogLayout frontmatter={frontmatter}>
  <p class="text-xl text-silver leading-relaxed mb-8">
    Quantum computers will break today's cryptography. Silica is ready.
  </p>

  <h2>The Quantum Threat</h2>
  <p>
    Current blockchain cryptography relies on mathematical problems that quantum computers can solve efficiently:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>ECDSA signatures:</strong> Shor's algorithm breaks elliptic curve cryptography</li>
    <li><strong>RSA:</strong> Also vulnerable to Shor's algorithm</li>
    <li><strong>Timeline:</strong> Cryptographically-relevant quantum computers expected within 10-15 years</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Chains designed today need to be secure tomorrow. Silica builds in quantum resistance from day one.
  </p>

  <h2>Post-Quantum Cryptography</h2>
  <p>
    Silica uses NIST-approved post-quantum algorithms:
  </p>

  <div class="tech-details">
    <h3>Signature Scheme: ML-DSA (Dilithium)</h3>
    <pre><code>// Primary signature algorithm
use pqcrypto_dilithium::dilithium3;

fn sign_transaction(tx: &amp;Transaction, sk: &amp;SecretKey) -&gt; Signature {'{'}
    dilithium3::sign(tx.hash(), sk)
{'}'}</code></pre>
    <p>Lattice-based signatures secure against both classical and quantum attacks.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Dual Key Architecture</h2>
  <p>
    Silica uses two key types for different purposes:
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Key Type</th>
        <th>Algorithm</th>
        <th>Purpose</th>
        <th>Rotation</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Identity Key</td>
        <td>Dilithium (PQ)</td>
        <td>Long-term identity, governance</td>
        <td>Rare</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="highlight">
        <td>Epoch Key</td>
        <td>EC-VRF</td>
        <td>Validator selection</td>
        <td>Every 5-10 min</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    Epoch keys use classical EC for performance in VRF operations, but rotate so frequently that even future quantum computers couldn't break them in time.
  </p>

  <h2>Byzantine Fault Tolerance</h2>
  <p>
    Beyond cryptography, Silica's consensus provides strong security guarantees:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Safety:</strong> Never commits conflicting transactions, even with 1/3 malicious validators</li>
    <li><strong>Liveness:</strong> Continues making progress with 2/3+ honest validators</li>
    <li><strong>Accountability:</strong> Misbehaving validators can be identified and slashed</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="info-box">
    <h3>Slashing Conditions</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Double signing:</strong> Signing conflicting blocks in the same round</li>
      <li><strong>Equivocation:</strong> Sending different messages to different validators</li>
      <li><strong>Unavailability:</strong> Extended downtime (for operators, not passive holders)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>Multi-Factor Validator Selection</h2>
  <p>
    Validator selection considers multiple factors to prevent gaming:
  </p>

  <div class="tech-details">
    <h3>Weight Formula</h3>
    <pre><code>w_i = (1 + stake_i)^0.5 × (rep_i)^1.0 × (geo_i)^1.2</code></pre>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Stake:</strong> Diminishing returns (square root) prevent plutocracy</li>
      <li><strong>Reputation:</strong> Linear weight rewards consistent performance</li>
      <li><strong>Geography:</strong> Slight boost for diversity prevents clustering</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>Defense in Depth</h2>
  <p>
    Security isn't just one layer—it's multiple overlapping protections:
  </p>

  <div class="benefits-grid">
    <div class="benefit-card">
      <h3>Cryptographic</h3>
      <p>Post-quantum signatures, hash-based commitments</p>
    </div>
    <div class="benefit-card">
      <h3>Economic</h3>
      <p>Slashing, stake requirements, reputation systems</p>
    </div>
    <div class="benefit-card">
      <h3>Architectural</h3>
      <p>Separation of concerns, validator rotation, geographic distribution</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Future-Proof Upgrades</h2>
  <p>
    Silica is designed for cryptographic agility:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Algorithm versioning:</strong> Signatures include algorithm identifiers</li>
    <li><strong>Smooth migration:</strong> Dual-signing during transition periods</li>
    <li><strong>Governance control:</strong> Algorithm updates via on-chain governance</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="cta-section">
    <h2>Security You Can Trust</h2>
    <p>
      Silica is designed for the long haul—secure against today's threats and tomorrow's quantum computers.
    </p>
    <p class="conclusion">
      Post-quantum ready. Byzantine resilient. Built for centuries.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="next-article">
    <p>
      <strong>Back to the beginning:</strong> Meet Chert Coin on the Silica Network — The complete introduction.
    </p>
  </div>
</BlogLayout>
